# read your datasets in here, e.g., with read_csv()

tracks <- read_csv("/stor/home/sv23377/tracks.csv")
artists <- read_csv("/stor/home/sv23377/artists.csv")

The tracks and artists datasets are taken from Spotify. The tracks data set has a list of songs with its popularity, duration in milliseconds, whether it is explicit, artist name, release date, danceability, energy, key, loudness, mode, tempo, etc. The artists dataset has the artists name, genre, popularity, and followers on Spotify. The Billboard Hot 100 is the music industry standard record chart in the United States for songs, published weekly by Billboard magazine. Chart rankings are based on sales, radio play, and online streaming in the United States. Finally, the charts dataset has the song name with its rank on on the Billboard Top100 with the artist name, week on billboard and date. The charts dataset has all Top100 songs from 1958 to July 2021. Data acquired from kaggle.com gathered by Pavan Sanagapati and Dhruvil Dave.

I am interested is these three datasets because it would be really cool to see the type of music that treads over the years because I do listen to music a lot, and my taste has changed significantly over the last ten years. It also seems that popular music has shifted from dance/EDM pop to more indie-sounding. These three datasets would be sufficient to see a preliminary correlation between genre and popularity. I would expect hip-hop, R&B, and indie to increase in popularity.

Tidying: Reshaping

If your datasets are tidy already, demonstrate that you can reshape data with pivot wider/longer here (e.g., untidy and then retidy). Alternatively, it may be easier to wait until the wrangling section so you can reshape your summary statistics. Note here if you are going to do this.

# Gets rid of the brackets in the columns 'artists' and
# 'id_artists.' Separates date of song release to year,
# month, and day
tracks <- tracks %>% mutate(artists = str_replace(artists, "\\['", 
    "")) %>% mutate(artists = str_replace(artists, "'\\]", "")) %>% 
    separate(artists, c("primary_artist", "ft_artist"), sep = "([','])", 
        remove = F) %>% mutate(id_artists = str_replace(id_artists, 
    "\\['", "")) %>% mutate(id_artists = str_replace(id_artists, 
    "'\\]", "")) %>% separate(release_date, c("re_year", "re_month", 
    "re_day"))

# Reshape 'artists' from wide to long
artists <- artists %>% mutate(genres = str_replace(genres, "\\[\\]", 
    "NA")) %>% pivot_longer(col = c("followers", "popularity"), 
    names_to = "type", values_to = "value")

# Reshape 'artists' long to wide
artists <- artists %>% pivot_wider(names_from = "type", values_from = "value")

tracks <- tracks %>% separate(id_artists, c("primary_artist_id", 
    "ft_artist_id"), sep = "([','])") %>% select(-ft_artist, 
    -ft_artist_id)

The brackets was gotten rid of in the columns artists and id_artists in the tracks dataset. The date of song release was split into year, month, and day. The artists was pivoted from wide to long and back. The tracks dataset contains an id column that is unique to each song and an artist_id column that is unique to each artist. If a song has multiple artists, the artist_id column has multiple artist ids that correspond to the id in the artists dataset. To make joining the artist dataset with the tracks dataset easier, I split the artist_id to only include the primary artist id.

# Dropped observations

    nrow(artists %>% anti_join(tracks, by = c(id = "primary_artist_id")))

# Cleaning up Columns
joined_dat <- joined_dat %>% mutate(song_name = name.x, song_popularity = popularity.x, 
    artist_popularity = popularity.y) %>% select(-name.y, -name.x, 
    -popularity.x, -popularity.y)

In the tracks dataset, there are 586672 observations. There are 1,104,349 observations in the artists dataset. There are 71531 unique artists in the tracks dataset." There are 1,104,349 unique artists in the artists dataset. There are 12,415 artists in the tracks dataset that are not in the artist dataset. There are 1,040,082 artists in the artists dataset that are not in the tracks dataset. There are 574,257 common ids in both datasets. The joined dataset is smaller that either of the tracks or artists dataset. I used inner join because when comparing popularity, it is useful to have both the song information and the artist popularity. 1052497 observations were dropped. The problem with this drop is that analysis with a partial dataset may not be accurate to real world data.

I created a sleepiness variable that takes into account the danceabiity, loudness, , energy, and tempo of the song to give a value that corresponds to how well one can sleep to the song. Since some of the variables such as danceability are on a different scale, I equalized some variables by multiplying by a hundred. I used regex to find the number of artists that start with lil. For the summary functions, I grouped by artists and found the mean danceability. I created a function num_distinct to find the number of distinct years the songs in the dataset have been released. Then, I used the min and max function to find the songs with the shorted and longest durations. I computed the sum of the standard deviation of each numeric variable to find the artist with the most range in music. Finally, I found the counts for each categorical variable.

Relaxation Sleep Meditation scored the highest for sleepiness, no surprise. Moriran by El Chombo scored the least for sleepiness. There are 143 artists that start with the name lil. Nu and Jo.Ke have the highest average danceability across all their songs. The song has 101 distinct years. The minimum duration of 3.344 seconds is by Louis Armstrong. The longest song is 936 minutes by Buddhadasa, a Thai ascetic-philosopher. Sergei Prokofiev and William Kapell have the most range. Around 130,000 observations do not have a month and/or the day of release.

Visualizing

sample_dat <- joined_dat %>% sample_frac(0.001)

# danceability vs energy
sample_dat %>% ggplot(aes(x = danceability, y = sleepiness)) + 
    geom_point(aes(color = "red"), show.legend = FALSE) + geom_smooth(method = "lm") + 
    scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 1, 0.1)) + labs(title = "Danceability and Sleepiness", 
    x = "Danceability", y = "Sleepiness")

Since there were too many datapoints to meaningfullly analyze anything, I took a ramdom fraction of the data for this plot. The plot depicts danceability plotted against sleepiness(computed in the previous section). A linear line was inserted with geom_smooth. The x-scale was changed to increase by 0.1. As danceability increases, sleepiness decreases. Danceability and sleepiness have a negative correlation.

joined_dat %>% filter(artists %in% c("Doja Cat", "Ariana Grande",
